export const reactAnswers: string[] = [
  "### Theory\n\nEvery component goes through three phases like a human life:\n\n**Mounting (Born)** - Component is created and placed on screen for the first time. This is where you initialize data and make your first API call.\n\n**Updating (Living)** - Something changes. User clicks, new data arrives, parent sends new props. The component re-renders to reflect the change.\n\n**Unmounting (Dying)** - Component is removed from screen. User navigated away, or a condition hid it. You clean up here - cancel timers, close connections.\n\n### Class Components - Each Phase Has a Named Method\n\n```jsx\nclass UserProfile extends React.Component {\n    // MOUNTING\n    constructor(props) {\n        super(props);\n        this.state = { user: null };\n        // Runs first. Set initial state here. Don't fetch data here.\n    }\n\n    componentDidMount() {\n        // Runs AFTER component appears on screen\n        // THE place for API calls, timers, subscriptions\n        fetchUser(this.props.userId).then(user => this.setState({ user }));\n    }\n\n    // UPDATING\n    componentDidUpdate(prevProps) {\n        // Runs AFTER every re-render (not on first mount)\n        // MUST have a condition or you get infinite loop\n        if (prevProps.userId !== this.props.userId) {\n            fetchUser(this.props.userId).then(user => this.setState({ user }));\n        }\n    }\n\n    // UNMOUNTING\n    componentWillUnmount() {\n        // Runs right before component is removed\n        // Cancel timers, unsubscribe, close connections\n        clearInterval(this.timer);\n    }\n\n    render() {\n        return <div>{this.state.user?.name}</div>;\n    }\n}\n```\n\n**Problem with class components:** Related logic is scattered. Setting up a subscription happens in `componentDidMount`, but cleaning it up happens in `componentWillUnmount`. These are the same concern but live in different methods.\n\n### Functional Components - Hooks Combine Everything\n\n```jsx\nfunction UserProfile({ userId }) {\n    const [user, setUser] = useState(null);\n\n    useEffect(() => {\n        // This ONE block handles mount + update + unmount\n        fetchUser(userId).then(setUser);     // setup (mount + update)\n        return () => cancelRequest();         // cleanup (unmount + before next run)\n    }, [userId]);\n\n    return <div>{user?.name}</div>;\n}\n```\n\n### The Key Difference\n\nClass = \"What lifecycle phase am I in?\"\nFunctional = \"What data does this effect depend on?\"\n\n```\nCLASS METHOD               ->  HOOK EQUIVALENT\nconstructor                ->  useState(initial)\ncomponentDidMount          ->  useEffect(() => {}, [])\ncomponentDidUpdate         ->  useEffect(() => {}, [dep])\ncomponentWillUnmount       ->  useEffect return function\nshouldComponentUpdate      ->  React.memo()\n```\n\n### Interview Answer\n\n> \"Every React component goes through mounting, updating, and unmounting. In class components, each phase has explicit methods - componentDidMount for setup, componentDidUpdate for changes, componentWillUnmount for cleanup. The problem is related logic gets scattered across methods - subscribing in one, unsubscribing in another.\n>\n> Functional components solve this with useEffect, which keeps related logic together. The dependency array controls when it runs, and the cleanup function handles teardown. Instead of thinking in lifecycle phases, I think in terms of synchronization - keep this effect in sync with these values.\n>\n> One difference I'm careful about: useEffect with dependencies also runs on mount, unlike componentDidUpdate which only runs on updates.\"",
  "### Theory\n\nBefore hooks (pre React 16.8), you could only use state and lifecycle in class components. This caused three problems:\n\n**Problem 1: Sharing logic was painful**\n\nIf two components needed the same logic (like fetching data), you had to use complicated patterns called Higher Order Components (HOCs) or render props.\n\n```jsx\n// Before hooks - wrapper hell\nconst EnhancedComponent = withAuth(withTheme(withData(MyComponent)));\n// Three wrappers deep - hard to read, hard to debug\n\n// After hooks - just call functions\nfunction MyComponent() {\n    const user = useAuth();\n    const theme = useTheme();\n    const data = useData();\n    // Clean, flat, readable\n}\n```\n\n**Problem 2: \"this\" was confusing**\n\n```jsx\n// Class - had to bind \"this\" everywhere or it broke\nclass Button extends React.Component {\n    constructor() {\n        super();\n        this.handleClick = this.handleClick.bind(this); // annoying boilerplate\n    }\n}\n\n// Hooks - no \"this\" at all\nfunction Button() {\n    const handleClick = () => console.log(\"clicked\"); // just works\n}\n```\n\n**Problem 3: Related code was split apart**\n\n```jsx\n// Class - subscribe in one method, unsubscribe in another\ncomponentDidMount() { subscribe(this.props.id); }\ncomponentWillUnmount() { unsubscribe(this.props.id); }\n\n// Hooks - together\nuseEffect(() => {\n    subscribe(id);\n    return () => unsubscribe(id); // right next to each other\n}, [id]);\n```\n\n### What Hooks Are\n\nHooks are functions that let you \"hook into\" React features from functional components. They all start with `use`:\n\n```\nuseState     - add state to a component\nuseEffect    - run side effects (API calls, timers)\nuseContext   - read shared data without prop drilling\nuseRef       - access DOM elements or store silent values\nuseMemo      - cache expensive calculations\nuseCallback  - cache function references\nuseReducer   - complex state logic (like Redux but local)\n```\n\n### Rules of Hooks\n\n```jsx\n// RULE 1: Only call at the TOP level - never inside if/else or loops\n// WRONG\nif (loggedIn) {\n    const [user, setUser] = useState(null); // BREAKS React\n}\n\n// RIGHT\nconst [user, setUser] = useState(null);\nif (loggedIn) { /* use user here */ }\n\n// RULE 2: Only call in React components or custom hooks\n// WRONG\nfunction regularFunction() {\n    const [x, setX] = useState(0); // BREAKS - not a component\n}\n```\n\n**Why the rules?** React tracks hooks by the ORDER they're called. If a hook is inside an `if`, the order might change between renders and React gets confused.\n\n### Interview Answer\n\n> \"Hooks were introduced in React 16.8 to solve three problems. First, sharing stateful logic required complex patterns like HOCs and render props - custom hooks make this trivial. Second, class components forced related logic across different lifecycle methods - useEffect keeps setup and cleanup together. Third, the 'this' keyword in classes confused both developers and tooling.\n>\n> Hooks let us write fully-featured components as functions, which are simpler to read, test, and optimize. The two rules are: only call at the top level, and only inside React components or custom hooks - because React relies on the call order to track state.\"",
  "### Theory\n\n**What is a side effect?** Anything that reaches OUTSIDE the component - API calls, timers, DOM manipulation, subscriptions, logging. These can't go directly in the component body because the function runs on every render.\n\n**useEffect says:** \"After you render, run this code.\"\n\n### The Dependency Array - Three Behaviors\n\n```jsx\n// 1. NO array - runs after EVERY render\nuseEffect(() => {\n    console.log(\"I run after every single render\");\n});\n// Use case: almost never. Usually a mistake.\n\n// 2. EMPTY array [] - runs ONCE after first render\nuseEffect(() => {\n    console.log(\"I run once when component appears\");\n    fetchInitialData();\n}, []);\n// Use case: initial data fetch, setup subscriptions\n\n// 3. WITH values [a, b] - runs when values change\nuseEffect(() => {\n    console.log(`userId changed to ${userId}`);\n    fetchUser(userId);\n}, [userId]);\n// Use case: react to specific changes\n```\n\n**Think of it as:** \"Re-run this effect whenever these values change.\"\n\n### Cleanup Function\n\nThe function you RETURN from useEffect runs in two situations:\n1. Before the effect runs again (dependency changed)\n2. When the component is removed from screen (unmount)\n\n```jsx\n// TIMER - must be cleaned up\nuseEffect(() => {\n    const id = setInterval(() => {\n        setSeconds(s => s + 1);\n    }, 1000);\n\n    return () => clearInterval(id); // cleanup: stop the timer\n}, []);\n\n// SUBSCRIPTION - must be cleaned up\nuseEffect(() => {\n    const ws = new WebSocket(\"wss://api.example.com\");\n    ws.onmessage = (msg) => setMessages(prev => [...prev, msg.data]);\n\n    return () => ws.close(); // cleanup: close connection\n}, []);\n\n// SEARCH - cancel previous request when query changes\nuseEffect(() => {\n    const controller = new AbortController();\n\n    fetch(`/api/search?q=${query}`, { signal: controller.signal })\n        .then(res => res.json())\n        .then(setResults);\n\n    return () => controller.abort(); // cleanup: cancel the old fetch\n}, [query]);\n```\n\n**Without cleanup:** Every render adds a NEW timer/subscription. After 100 renders, 100 timers are running. Memory leak.\n\n### Interview Answer\n\n> \"useEffect runs side effects after render - things like API calls, subscriptions, and timers that can't go in the render path. The dependency array controls when it re-runs: empty means once on mount, with values means when those change, no array means every render.\n>\n> The cleanup function is critical - it runs before the next effect and on unmount. I use it to cancel API requests, clear timers, and close WebSocket connections. A common pattern is a search input where each keystroke triggers a fetch - the cleanup aborts the previous request before starting a new one, preventing race conditions.\"",
  "### Theory\n\n`useState` lets you add data to a component that can change over time. When the data changes, the component re-renders to show the new value.\n\n```jsx\nconst [count, setCount] = useState(0);\n//      ^        ^                 ^\n//  current    function to      starting\n//  value      update it        value\n```\n\n### How Batching Works\n\nReact doesn't apply state updates immediately. It batches them - waits for all updates in the same event handler, then does one re-render.\n\n```jsx\nfunction Counter() {\n    const [count, setCount] = useState(0);\n\n    function handleClick() {\n        setCount(count + 1);  // count is still 0\n        setCount(count + 1);  // count is STILL 0 - uses stale value\n        setCount(count + 1);  // count is STILL 0\n        // Result: count goes from 0 to 1, NOT 3\n        // Because all three reads see count = 0\n    }\n\n    // FIX: use the functional form\n    function handleClickCorrect() {\n        setCount(prev => prev + 1);  // prev = 0 -> returns 1\n        setCount(prev => prev + 1);  // prev = 1 -> returns 2\n        setCount(prev => prev + 1);  // prev = 2 -> returns 3\n        // Result: count goes from 0 to 3 [ok]\n    }\n}\n```\n\n**Why batching?** Without it, three setCount calls would cause three re-renders. With batching, React combines them into one re-render. Better performance.\n\n### Limitations\n\n**1. State updates are asynchronous - you can't read the new value immediately**\n```jsx\nfunction handleClick() {\n    setCount(count + 1);\n    console.log(count);  // still the OLD value!\n    // The new value is only available on the NEXT render\n}\n```\n\n**2. useState doesn't merge objects - you must spread manually**\n```jsx\nconst [user, setUser] = useState({ name: \"\", age: 0, email: \"\" });\n\n// WRONG - loses age and email\nsetUser({ name: \"Alice\" });\n// Result: { name: \"Alice\" } - age and email are GONE\n\n// CORRECT - spread to keep other fields\nsetUser(prev => ({ ...prev, name: \"Alice\" }));\n// Result: { name: \"Alice\", age: 0, email: \"\" }\n```\n\n**3. Never mutate state directly**\n```jsx\n// WRONG - React doesn't detect the change, no re-render\nconst [items, setItems] = useState([\"a\", \"b\"]);\nitems.push(\"c\");       // mutating the existing array\nsetItems(items);        // React sees the SAME reference - does nothing\n\n// CORRECT - create a new array\nsetItems([...items, \"c\"]);\n```\n\n### Interview Answer\n\n> \"useState returns the current value and a setter function. State updates are asynchronous and batched - React combines multiple updates in the same handler into one re-render for performance. If you need to update based on the previous value, use the functional form: setState(prev => prev + 1).\n>\n> Key limitations: you can't read the new value immediately after setting it, objects aren't merged automatically like class setState, and you must never mutate state directly - always create new references. For complex state with many fields or interdependent updates, I switch to useReducer.\"",
  "### Theory\n\nEvery time a component re-renders, ALL code inside it runs again - every calculation, every function creation. Usually this is fine and instant. But sometimes it's slow.\n\n**useMemo** - caches the RESULT of a calculation. Only recalculates when dependencies change.\n\n**useCallback** - caches a FUNCTION itself. Only recreates when dependencies change.\n\n### useMemo\n\n```jsx\nfunction ProductList({ products, filter }) {\n    // WITHOUT useMemo - filters 10,000 products on EVERY render\n    // Even if you just typed in a search box that has nothing to do with products\n    const filtered = products.filter(p => p.category === filter);\n\n    // WITH useMemo - only re-filters when products or filter actually change\n    const filtered = useMemo(() => {\n        return products.filter(p => p.category === filter);\n    }, [products, filter]);\n\n    return filtered.map(p => <div key={p.id}>{p.name}</div>);\n}\n```\n\n### useCallback\n\n```jsx\nfunction Parent() {\n    const [count, setCount] = useState(0);\n\n    // WITHOUT useCallback - new function every render\n    // Child thinks it got new props -> re-renders unnecessarily\n    const handleClick = () => console.log(\"clicked\");\n\n    // WITH useCallback - same function reference between renders\n    const handleClick = useCallback(() => {\n        console.log(\"clicked\");\n    }, []); // same reference unless dependencies change\n\n    return <MemoizedChild onClick={handleClick} />;\n}\n\n// Child wrapped in React.memo - only re-renders if props change\nconst MemoizedChild = React.memo(({ onClick }) => {\n    console.log(\"Child rendered\");\n    return <button onClick={onClick}>Click</button>;\n});\n```\n\n**useCallback is ONLY useful with React.memo.** If the child isn't memoized, it re-renders anyway, making useCallback pointless.\n\n### When NOT to Use Them\n\n```jsx\n// UNNECESSARY - simple math, faster without useMemo\nconst total = useMemo(() => price * quantity, [price, quantity]);\n// price * quantity takes nanoseconds - useMemo overhead is worse\n\n// UNNECESSARY - useCallback without React.memo on child\nconst handleClick = useCallback(() => doSomething(), []);\n<NormalChild onClick={handleClick} />\n// NormalChild re-renders anyway because parent re-rendered\n```\n\n**Rule:** Don't add them by default. Profile first, optimize where measured.\n\n### Interview Answer\n\n> \"useMemo caches a computed value, useCallback caches a function reference - both recalculate only when dependencies change. I use useMemo for expensive computations like filtering large datasets, and useCallback when passing functions to React.memo-wrapped children to prevent unnecessary re-renders.\n>\n> I don't add them by default - they have overhead. I profile with React DevTools first and add them only where I measure an actual performance problem. Premature optimization with these hooks can actually make code slower and harder to read.\"",
  "### Theory\n\n**Props** - data passed INTO a component from its parent. Like function arguments. Read-only.\n\n**State** - data owned BY the component internally. Like local variables that persist between renders. Can be changed.\n\n```jsx\n// PROPS - come from outside, can't be changed\nfunction Welcome({ name, age }) {   // parent decides these values\n    // name = \"Bob\";  <- WRONG - can't modify props\n    return <h1>Hello {name}, age {age}</h1>;\n}\n\n// STATE - owned inside, can be changed\nfunction Counter() {\n    const [count, setCount] = useState(0);  // component owns this\n    return <button onClick={() => setCount(count + 1)}>{count}</button>;\n}\n```\n\n**Can a component modify its own props?** NO. Never. Props flow one way - parent to child. If a child needs to change something the parent controls, the parent passes a callback:\n\n```jsx\nfunction Parent() {\n    const [name, setName] = useState(\"Alice\");\n    return <Child name={name} onNameChange={setName} />;\n}\n\nfunction Child({ name, onNameChange }) {\n    // Can't do: name = \"Bob\"\n    // Instead: ask parent to change it\n    return <button onClick={() => onNameChange(\"Bob\")}>Change Name</button>;\n}\n```\n\n### Interview Answer\n\n> \"Props are read-only data passed from parent to child - the child cannot modify them. State is data owned and managed by the component itself, updated via setState. If a child needs to change something the parent controls, the parent passes a callback as a prop.\n>\n> This one-way data flow is fundamental to React - data flows down through props, actions flow up through callbacks. It makes the app predictable and easier to debug because you always know where data comes from.\"",
  "### Theory\n\nA custom hook is a regular JavaScript function that starts with `use` and can call other hooks. It lets you extract reusable logic that involves state or effects.\n\n**Key point:** The LOGIC is shared, not the STATE. Every component that calls the hook gets its own independent copy of the state.\n\n### useFetch - Reusable Data Fetching\n\n```jsx\nfunction useFetch(url) {\n    const [data, setData] = useState(null);\n    const [loading, setLoading] = useState(true);\n    const [error, setError] = useState(null);\n\n    useEffect(() => {\n        let cancelled = false;\n        setLoading(true);\n        setError(null);\n\n        fetch(url)\n            .then(res => {\n                if (!res.ok) throw new Error(`HTTP ${res.status}`);\n                return res.json();\n            })\n            .then(data => {\n                if (!cancelled) { setData(data); setLoading(false); }\n            })\n            .catch(err => {\n                if (!cancelled) { setError(err.message); setLoading(false); }\n            });\n\n        return () => { cancelled = true; };\n    }, [url]);\n\n    return { data, loading, error };\n}\n\n// USE IT ANYWHERE - no duplicate code\nfunction UserList() {\n    const { data: users, loading, error } = useFetch(\"/api/users\");\n    if (loading) return <Spinner />;\n    if (error) return <p>Error: {error}</p>;\n    return users.map(u => <div key={u.id}>{u.name}</div>);\n}\n\nfunction OrderList() {\n    const { data: orders, loading, error } = useFetch(\"/api/orders\");\n    // Same pattern, zero duplicate logic\n}\n```\n\n### useDebounce - Delay Until User Stops Typing\n\n```jsx\nfunction useDebounce(value, delay) {\n    const [debouncedValue, setDebouncedValue] = useState(value);\n\n    useEffect(() => {\n        const timer = setTimeout(() => setDebouncedValue(value), delay);\n        return () => clearTimeout(timer);\n    }, [value, delay]);\n\n    return debouncedValue;\n}\n\n// Usage\nfunction Search() {\n    const [query, setQuery] = useState(\"\");\n    const debouncedQuery = useDebounce(query, 300);\n\n    useEffect(() => {\n        if (debouncedQuery) searchApi(debouncedQuery);\n    }, [debouncedQuery]); // only fires 300ms after user stops typing\n\n    return <input value={query} onChange={e => setQuery(e.target.value)} />;\n}\n```\n\n### Interview Answer\n\n> \"A custom hook is a function starting with 'use' that encapsulates reusable stateful logic. I've built useFetch for data fetching with loading/error states, useDebounce for delaying API calls until the user stops typing, and useLocalStorage for persisting state. The key is that each component calling the hook gets its own independent state - the logic is shared, not the data.\"",
  "### Theory\n\n**Controlled** - React state is the source of truth. Every keystroke goes through React.\n\n```jsx\nfunction LoginForm() {\n    const [email, setEmail] = useState(\"\");\n\n    return (\n        <input\n            value={email}                           // React says what's displayed\n            onChange={e => setEmail(e.target.value)} // Every keystroke -> state -> re-render\n        />\n    );\n    // You always know what's in the input - it's in state\n    // You can validate, format, disable submit based on input\n}\n```\n\n**Uncontrolled** - The DOM is the source of truth. React doesn't know the value until you ask.\n\n```jsx\nfunction LoginForm() {\n    const emailRef = useRef();\n\n    function handleSubmit() {\n        console.log(emailRef.current.value); // grab value only when needed\n    }\n\n    return (\n        <div>\n            <input ref={emailRef} />\n            <button onClick={handleSubmit}>Submit</button>\n        </div>\n    );\n}\n```\n\n### When to Use Which\n\n```\nControlled  ->  Real-time validation, formatting, disabling submit, most forms\nUncontrolled -> File inputs (can't set file value), simple one-shot forms\n```\n\n### Interview Answer\n\n> \"In controlled components, React state drives the input - every change goes through setState, giving full control for validation and formatting. In uncontrolled, the DOM holds the value and you read it via refs. I default to controlled for most forms because I need real-time validation. Uncontrolled is for file inputs since you can't programmatically set file values, and sometimes for performance-critical forms where re-rendering on every keystroke is too expensive.\"",
  "### Theory\n\n**The Problem:** Real DOM operations are slow. If you change one item in a list of 1000, re-creating all 1000 DOM nodes is wasteful.\n\n**Virtual DOM** - A lightweight JavaScript copy of the real DOM. It's just a plain object describing the UI structure. Updating a JavaScript object is extremely fast.\n\n**How it works:**\n\n```\n1. State changes (user clicks, data arrives)\n2. React creates a NEW Virtual DOM tree (just a JS object)\n3. React COMPARES new tree with previous tree (this is \"diffing\")\n4. React finds the MINIMUM changes needed\n5. React applies ONLY those changes to the real DOM\n```\n\n**Diffing Algorithm - Three Rules:**\n\n**Rule 1: Different element type = destroy and rebuild entire subtree**\n```jsx\n// Before\n<div><Counter /></div>\n\n// After\n<span><Counter /></span>\n\n// div -> span = different type\n// React destroys <div> and EVERYTHING inside it (including Counter's state)\n// Rebuilds from scratch inside <span>\n```\n\n**Rule 2: Same element type = update only changed attributes**\n```jsx\n// Before\n<div className=\"old\" style={{color: \"red\"}} />\n\n// After\n<div className=\"new\" style={{color: \"blue\"}} />\n\n// Same type (div) -> keep the DOM node, just update className and style\n```\n\n**Rule 3: Lists use keys to identify items**\n```jsx\n// Without keys - React compares by position\n// Remove first item -> React thinks EVERYTHING shifted -> updates every item\n\n// With keys - React matches by key\n// Remove first item -> React knows exactly which one was removed -> removes only that\n```\n\nThis makes React's diff O(n) instead of O(n^3) for a generic tree comparison.\n\n### Interview Answer\n\n> \"The Virtual DOM is a lightweight JavaScript representation of the real DOM. When state changes, React creates a new Virtual DOM, diffs it against the previous one, and applies the minimum necessary changes to the real DOM.\n>\n> The diffing algorithm uses three heuristics: elements of different types produce entirely different trees, same-type elements get their attributes updated in place, and list children are matched by key props. This reduces the complexity from O(n^3) to O(n), making updates fast even for large component trees.\"",
  "### Theory\n\n**Reconciliation** is the entire process of deciding what changed and updating the DOM. Diffing is the comparison step within reconciliation.\n\n**The key prop** tells React which item is which in a list. Without it, React matches by position.\n\n```jsx\n// WITHOUT keys - removing \"Alice\" confuses React\n// React sees position 0 changed from Alice to Bob, position 1 changed from Bob to Charlie\n// It updates TWO nodes instead of removing ONE\n<ul>\n    <li>Alice</li>   {/* React thinks: \"became Bob\" -> update */}\n    <li>Bob</li>     {/* React thinks: \"became Charlie\" -> update */}\n    <li>Charlie</li> {/* React thinks: \"removed\" -> delete */}\n</ul>\n\n// WITH keys - React knows exactly what happened\n<ul>\n    <li key=\"alice\">Alice</li>     {/* removed */}\n    <li key=\"bob\">Bob</li>         {/* unchanged */}\n    <li key=\"charlie\">Charlie</li> {/* unchanged */}\n</ul>\n// React removes only Alice's node. Much faster.\n```\n\n**Never use array index as key for dynamic lists:**\n```jsx\n// BAD - if items reorder, index doesn't follow the item\n{items.map((item, index) => <li key={index}>{item}</li>)}\n\n// GOOD - unique stable ID\n{items.map(item => <li key={item.id}>{item.name}</li>)}\n```\n\n### Interview Answer\n\n> \"Reconciliation is how React determines what to update in the DOM. It builds a new Virtual DOM, diffs against the old one, and applies minimum changes. The key prop is critical for lists - it lets React identify which items moved, changed, or were removed without comparing every element by position. I always use stable unique IDs as keys, never array indices, because indices break when items are reordered or deleted.\"",
  "### Theory\n\n**Context API** - Built into React. Share data without passing props through every level.\n\n```jsx\nconst ThemeContext = createContext(\"light\");\n\n// Provide\n<ThemeContext.Provider value={theme}>\n    <App />\n</ThemeContext.Provider>\n\n// Consume - anywhere deep\nconst theme = useContext(ThemeContext);\n```\n\n**Problem with Context:** When the value changes, EVERY component that consumes it re-renders - even if it only uses part of the value.\n\n**Redux / Zustand** - External libraries. Components subscribe to specific slices. Only re-renders when THEIR slice changes.\n\n```\nCONTEXT                          REDUX / ZUSTAND\nBuilt-in, simple              ->  External library, more setup\nRe-renders ALL consumers      ->  Re-renders only affected ones\nNo middleware or devtools     ->  Time-travel debugging, middleware\nTheme, auth, locale           ->  Complex app state, many actions\n```\n\n### Interview Answer\n\n> \"I use Context for simple, rarely-changing state - theme, authentication, locale. For server data, I use React Query which handles caching and background refetching. For complex client-side state, I'd use Zustand - simpler than Redux but gives selective re-rendering. The problem with Context for frequently-changing data is every consumer re-renders on any change, which hurts performance in large apps.\"",
  "### Theory\n\n**1. Code Splitting** - Don't load everything upfront. Load pages on demand.\n\n```jsx\nconst Dashboard = React.lazy(() => import(\"./Dashboard\"));\n\nfunction App() {\n    return (\n        <Suspense fallback={<Spinner />}>\n            <Dashboard /> {/* code downloads only when rendered */}\n        </Suspense>\n    );\n}\n```\n\n**2. React.memo** - Skip re-rendering if props didn't change.\n\n```jsx\nconst ExpensiveList = React.memo(({ items }) => {\n    return items.map(i => <div key={i.id}>{i.name}</div>);\n});\n// Only re-renders when items actually changes\n```\n\n**3. Virtualization** - For huge lists, render only visible items.\n\n```jsx\nimport { FixedSizeList } from \"react-window\";\n// 10,000 items but only ~20 DOM nodes exist at any time\n```\n\n**4. Debouncing** - Don't fire API calls on every keystroke.\n\n**5. useMemo/useCallback** - Cache expensive calculations and function references.\n\n### Interview Answer\n\n> \"I approach optimization by measuring first with React DevTools Profiler. Code splitting with React.lazy reduces initial bundle size - I split by route. React.memo prevents unnecessary re-renders of expensive children. For long lists, virtualization with react-window renders only visible items. I debounce search inputs and use useMemo only for genuinely expensive computations.\"",
  "### Theory\n\n**Prop drilling** is when you pass data through many layers of components that don't use it.\n\n```jsx\nApp -> Layout -> Sidebar -> UserMenu -> Avatar\n// Layout and Sidebar don't use \"user\" - they just pass it through\n```\n\n**Solutions:**\n\n```jsx\n// 1. CONTEXT - skip the middle layers\nconst UserContext = createContext();\n\nfunction App() {\n    return (\n        <UserContext.Provider value={user}>\n            <Layout />  {/* no user prop */}\n        </UserContext.Provider>\n    );\n}\n\nfunction Avatar() {\n    const user = useContext(UserContext); // grabs it directly\n}\n\n// 2. COMPOSITION - pass components, not data\nfunction App() {\n    return <Layout sidebar={<Sidebar avatar={<Avatar user={user} />} />} />;\n    // Layout doesn't know about user at all\n}\n```\n\n### Interview Answer\n\n> \"Prop drilling is passing data through intermediate components that don't use it. For global data like auth or theme, I use Context. For targeted cases, I use component composition - passing rendered components as props so middle layers don't need the data. For server state, React Query eliminates drilling because any component can call useQuery with the same key and get cached data.\"",
  "### Theory\n\n```\nuseState  -> changes trigger re-render  -> for data shown on screen\nuseRef    -> changes are SILENT          -> for internal tracking, DOM access\n```\n\n```jsx\nfunction Timer() {\n    const [count, setCount] = useState(0);   // shown on screen -> needs re-render\n    const intervalRef = useRef(null);         // internal tracking -> no re-render\n\n    function start() {\n        intervalRef.current = setInterval(() => {\n            setCount(prev => prev + 1);\n        }, 1000);\n    }\n\n    function stop() {\n        clearInterval(intervalRef.current); // access without re-rendering\n    }\n\n    return <p>{count}</p>;\n}\n```\n\n**useRef for DOM access:**\n```jsx\nconst inputRef = useRef();\n<input ref={inputRef} />\ninputRef.current.focus(); // directly manipulate the DOM element\n```\n\n### Interview Answer\n\n> \"useState triggers a re-render on update - use it for anything visible in the UI. useRef persists a value across renders without re-rendering - use it for DOM references, interval IDs, previous values, or any mutable value the UI doesn't directly display. I use useRef for storing timer IDs so I can clear them later without causing unnecessary re-renders.\"",
  "### Theory\n\nPortals render a component into a different DOM node, outside its parent hierarchy. Useful when CSS would trap the component (overflow: hidden, z-index).\n\n```jsx\nimport { createPortal } from \"react-dom\";\n\nfunction Modal({ children, isOpen }) {\n    if (!isOpen) return null;\n    return createPortal(\n        <div className=\"modal-overlay\">{children}</div>,\n        document.getElementById(\"modal-root\") // renders HERE, not inside parent\n    );\n}\n```\n\nEven though the modal is in a different DOM node, React events still bubble through the React tree normally.\n\n### Interview Answer\n\n> \"Portals render into a different DOM node outside the parent hierarchy. I use them for modals, tooltips, and dropdowns that need to break out of containers with overflow hidden or z-index stacking contexts. Events still bubble through the React component tree normally, which is important for maintaining expected behavior.\"",
  "### Theory\n\nIn plain HTML, you'd attach a listener to every button. 100 buttons = 100 listeners.\n\nReact attaches ONE listener to the root element. When any event happens, it bubbles up to root, and React figures out which component handler to call.\n\n```jsx\n// You write:\n<button onClick={handleClick}>Click</button>\n\n// React does NOT do:\nbutton.addEventListener(\"click\", handleClick);\n\n// React actually does:\nroot.addEventListener(\"click\", (e) => {\n    // find which React component this came from -> call its handler\n});\n```\n\nReact also wraps events in **SyntheticEvent** - a cross-browser wrapper that normalizes behavior.\n\n### Interview Answer\n\n> \"React uses event delegation - one listener on the root, not on every element. When an event bubbles up, React uses its fiber tree to route it to the correct handler. This is memory efficient and handles dynamic components automatically. Events are also wrapped in SyntheticEvents for cross-browser consistency.\"",
  "### Theory\n\n```\nuseEffect       -> runs AFTER the browser paints pixels on screen\nuseLayoutEffect -> runs BEFORE the browser paints\n```\n\n```jsx\n// useEffect - user might see a flash\nuseEffect(() => {\n    const rect = ref.current.getBoundingClientRect();\n    setPosition({ top: rect.bottom }); // screen painted THEN moved -> flicker\n}, []);\n\n// useLayoutEffect - no flash\nuseLayoutEffect(() => {\n    const rect = ref.current.getBoundingClientRect();\n    setPosition({ top: rect.bottom }); // calculated BEFORE paint -> smooth\n}, []);\n```\n\n**Rule:** Use useEffect for 99% of cases. Switch to useLayoutEffect only when you see visual flickering from DOM measurements.\n\n### Interview Answer\n\n> \"useEffect runs after the browser paints, which is fine for data fetching and most side effects. useLayoutEffect runs synchronously before paint, necessary for DOM measurements like positioning tooltips where you'd otherwise see a flicker. I default to useEffect and only switch when I observe visual jank from layout calculations.\"",
  "### Theory\n\nIf a component throws during render, the entire app crashes. Error boundaries catch errors in children and show a fallback.\n\n```jsx\nclass ErrorBoundary extends React.Component {\n    state = { hasError: false };\n\n    static getDerivedStateFromError(error) {\n        return { hasError: true };\n    }\n\n    componentDidCatch(error, info) {\n        logErrorToService(error, info);\n    }\n\n    render() {\n        if (this.state.hasError) return <h2>Something went wrong</h2>;\n        return this.props.children;\n    }\n}\n\n// Wrap sections separately\n<ErrorBoundary>\n    <Header />       {/* Header crash doesn't kill Dashboard */}\n</ErrorBoundary>\n<ErrorBoundary>\n    <Dashboard />\n</ErrorBoundary>\n```\n\n**Don't catch:** event handlers (use try-catch), async code, server rendering.\n\n### Interview Answer\n\n> \"Error boundaries are class components that catch render errors in children and show a fallback UI instead of crashing the app. I wrap major sections separately so a crash in one doesn't take down the whole page. They use getDerivedStateFromError for fallback rendering and componentDidCatch for logging. There's no hook equivalent yet, so they must be class components.\"",
  "### Theory\n\n**Before Fiber (React 15):** Rendering was synchronous. If updating 10,000 nodes took 2 seconds, the UI froze for 2 seconds.\n\n**After Fiber (React 16+):** Rendering is broken into small chunks. React can pause, check for user input, handle it, then resume rendering.\n\n**Key features:**\n- Incremental rendering - break work into chunks\n- Priority - user input > animations > data fetching\n- Pause/resume - can stop mid-render\n- Abort - discard incomplete work if higher priority arrives\n\n### Interview Answer\n\n> \"Fiber is React's reconciliation engine introduced in React 16. It splits rendering into chunks spread across frames instead of blocking the main thread. React can pause to handle high-priority work like user input, then resume. This enables concurrent features like Suspense and prevents the UI from freezing during large updates.\"",
  "### Theory\n\nWhen siblings need shared state, move it to their closest common parent.\n\n```jsx\nfunction TemperatureConverter() {\n    const [fahrenheit, setFahrenheit] = useState(32);\n    const celsius = ((fahrenheit - 32) * 5) / 9;\n\n    return (\n        <div>\n            <input value={fahrenheit}\n                   onChange={e => setFahrenheit(Number(e.target.value))} />\n            <p>Celsius: {celsius.toFixed(1)}</p>\n            {/* Both stay in sync because they share the same source of truth */}\n        </div>\n    );\n}\n```\n\n### Interview Answer\n\n> \"When two siblings need access to the same data, I lift the state to their closest common parent. The parent owns the state and passes it down as props, along with callbacks for children to request changes. This maintains a single source of truth. If the state needs to be shared across many distant components, that's when I switch to Context.\"",
  "### Theory\n\nSuspense shows a fallback while something is loading.\n\n```jsx\nconst Dashboard = React.lazy(() => import(\"./Dashboard\"));\n\nfunction App() {\n    return (\n        <Suspense fallback={<Spinner />}>\n            <Dashboard /> {/* Spinner shows while code downloads */}\n        </Suspense>\n    );\n}\n```\n\nMost commonly used for route-based code splitting - each page loads on demand.\n\n### Interview Answer\n\n> \"Suspense declaratively handles loading states for lazy-loaded components. I use it with React.lazy for route-based code splitting so each page's bundle loads on demand, reducing initial load time. In newer React versions, it also works with data fetching libraries, allowing components to suspend until data is ready.\"",
  "### Theory\n\n**Controlled (manual)** - lots of boilerplate, every field needs state + onChange + validation.\n\n**React Hook Form** - less code, fewer re-renders, validation built in.\n\n```jsx\nimport { useForm } from \"react-hook-form\";\n\nfunction SignupForm() {\n    const { register, handleSubmit, formState: { errors } } = useForm();\n\n    return (\n        <div>\n            <input {...register(\"email\", {\n                required: \"Email required\",\n                pattern: { value: /\\S+@\\S+/, message: \"Invalid email\" }\n            })} />\n            {errors.email && <span>{errors.email.message}</span>}\n            <button onClick={handleSubmit(onSubmit)}>Submit</button>\n        </div>\n    );\n}\n```\n\n### Interview Answer\n\n> \"For simple forms I use controlled components with useState. For complex forms with validation and many fields, I use React Hook Form - it uses uncontrolled components internally so it minimizes re-renders, and validation is declarative. Especially good for dynamic fields and nested data.\"",
  "### Theory\n\nDevelopment-only tool that finds bugs by intentionally double-rendering components and double-firing effects.\n\n```jsx\n<React.StrictMode>\n    <App />\n</React.StrictMode>\n```\n\n- Double-renders to catch side effects in render\n- Double-fires useEffect to catch missing cleanup\n- Warns about deprecated APIs\n- Zero impact on production\n\n### Interview Answer\n\n> \"StrictMode is a dev-only wrapper that intentionally double-renders and double-fires effects to expose bugs - especially missing cleanup functions and unintentional side effects. It helped me catch a WebSocket connection that wasn't being closed properly. No impact on production builds.\"",
  "### Theory\n\n**Pagination:** Fetch one page at a time, show next/previous buttons.\n\n**Infinite scroll:** Use IntersectionObserver on the last item - when visible, fetch next page.\n\n```jsx\nfunction InfiniteList() {\n    const [items, setItems] = useState([]);\n    const [page, setPage] = useState(1);\n    const [hasMore, setHasMore] = useState(true);\n    const observerRef = useRef();\n\n    useEffect(() => {\n        fetch(`/api/items?page=${page}`)\n            .then(res => res.json())\n            .then(data => {\n                setItems(prev => [...prev, ...data]); // APPEND\n                setHasMore(data.length === 20);\n            });\n    }, [page]);\n\n    const lastItemRef = useCallback(node => {\n        if (observerRef.current) observerRef.current.disconnect();\n        observerRef.current = new IntersectionObserver(entries => {\n            if (entries[0].isIntersecting && hasMore) setPage(p => p + 1);\n        });\n        if (node) observerRef.current.observe(node);\n    }, [hasMore]);\n\n    return items.map((item, i) => (\n        <div key={item.id} ref={i === items.length - 1 ? lastItemRef : null}>\n            {item.name}\n        </div>\n    ));\n}\n```\n\n### Interview Answer\n\n> \"For pagination, I fetch one page at a time with next/previous controls. For infinite scroll, I attach an IntersectionObserver to the last rendered item - when it enters the viewport, I increment the page and append new data. Key details: append, don't replace; use useCallback for the observer ref; track a hasMore flag. In production, I'd use React Query's useInfiniteQuery.\""
];

export const javascriptAnswers: string[] = [
  "### Theory\n\nBoth limit how often a function runs, but differently.\n\n**Debouncing** - \"Wait until the user STOPS doing something, then run.\" Like a elevator door - it waits until people stop entering, then closes.\n\n**Throttling** - \"Run at most once every X milliseconds.\" Like a machine gun with a cooldown - fires, waits, fires, waits.\n\n### From Scratch\n\n```js\n// DEBOUNCE - run after user stops\nfunction debounce(fn, delay) {\n    let timer;\n    return function(...args) {\n        clearTimeout(timer);             // cancel previous\n        timer = setTimeout(() => {\n            fn.apply(this, args);        // run after silence\n        }, delay);\n    };\n}\n\n// User types: h-e-l-l-o (each 100ms apart)\n// Only calls API once, 300ms after the \"o\"\nconst search = debounce(query => fetch(`/api?q=${query}`), 300);\n\n\n// THROTTLE - run at most once per interval\nfunction throttle(fn, limit) {\n    let inThrottle = false;\n    return function(...args) {\n        if (!inThrottle) {\n            fn.apply(this, args);        // run immediately\n            inThrottle = true;\n            setTimeout(() => {\n                inThrottle = false;      // allow next call after limit\n            }, limit);\n        }\n    };\n}\n\n// User scrolls continuously\n// Handler fires at most once per 200ms, not on every pixel\nconst onScroll = throttle(() => console.log(\"scrolled\"), 200);\n```\n\n```\nUse debounce for: search input, form validation, window resize, auto-save\nUse throttle for: scroll events, mouse move, game input, API polling\n```\n\n### Interview Answer\n\n> \"Debouncing delays execution until the user stops triggering - I use it for search inputs so the API isn't hit on every keystroke. Throttling ensures a function runs at most once per interval - I use it for scroll handlers and resize events. Both prevent performance issues from rapid-fire events. I can implement both from scratch using closures and setTimeout.\"",
  "### Theory\n\n**Callback hell** - nested callbacks that form a pyramid of doom.\n\n```js\n// CALLBACK HELL - unreadable, undebuggable\ngetUser(userId, function(user) {\n    getOrders(user.id, function(orders) {\n        getOrderDetails(orders[0].id, function(details) {\n            getShipping(details.id, function(shipping) {\n                console.log(shipping);\n                // 4 levels deep. Error handling? Good luck.\n            });\n        });\n    });\n});\n\n// PROMISES - flat chain\ngetUser(userId)\n    .then(user => getOrders(user.id))\n    .then(orders => getOrderDetails(orders[0].id))\n    .then(details => getShipping(details.id))\n    .then(shipping => console.log(shipping))\n    .catch(err => console.log(\"Any error caught here\"));\n\n// ASYNC/AWAIT - reads like synchronous code\nasync function getShippingInfo(userId) {\n    try {\n        const user = await getUser(userId);\n        const orders = await getOrders(user.id);\n        const details = await getOrderDetails(orders[0].id);\n        const shipping = await getShipping(details.id);\n        console.log(shipping);\n    } catch (err) {\n        console.log(\"Any error caught here\");\n    }\n}\n```\n\n### Interview Answer\n\n> \"Callback hell is deeply nested callbacks that are hard to read and debug. Promises flatten this into a chain with .then() and centralized error handling with .catch(). Async/await goes further - it makes asynchronous code read like synchronous code with try/catch for errors. Under the hood, async/await is syntactic sugar over Promises.\"",
  "### Theory\n\nJavaScript is single-threaded - one thing at a time. The event loop is how it handles async operations without blocking.\n\n```\n+---------------------+\n|     CALL STACK       |  <- runs synchronous code, one function at a time\n+---------+-----------+\n          |\n          v when stack is empty\n+---------------------+\n|  MICROTASK QUEUE     |  <- Promises, queueMicrotask (HIGH priority)\n+---------+-----------+\n          |\n          v when microtasks are done\n+---------------------+\n|  MACROTASK QUEUE     |  <- setTimeout, setInterval, I/O (LOW priority)\n+---------------------+\n```\n\n```js\nconsole.log(\"1\");                              // sync -> stack\nsetTimeout(() => console.log(\"2\"), 0);         // macrotask -> queue\nPromise.resolve().then(() => console.log(\"3\")); // microtask -> queue\nconsole.log(\"4\");                              // sync -> stack\n\n// Output: 1, 4, 3, 2\n// Sync first, then microtasks, then macrotasks\n```\n\n### Interview Answer\n\n> \"The event loop is how JavaScript handles concurrency on a single thread. Synchronous code runs on the call stack. When async work completes, its callback goes into a queue. Microtasks like Promises have higher priority than macrotasks like setTimeout. The loop continuously checks: stack empty? Run all microtasks. Then run one macrotask. Repeat. This is why a Promise with .then resolves before a setTimeout with 0ms delay.\"",
  "### Theory\n\n**Single-threaded** means JavaScript can only execute one piece of code at a time. There's one call stack, one thread of execution.\n\n**Async/await doesn't create new threads.** It says \"start this I/O operation, hand it off to the OS/browser, free the thread, come back when results are ready.\"\n\n```\nSYNC:   [Task A 3sec][Task B 3sec][Task C 3sec] = 9 seconds total\n\nASYNC:  [Start A][Start B][Start C]...[A done][B done][C done] = ~3 seconds\n        All three started, thread freed during wait, results arrive later\n```\n\nIt's not parallelism (multiple things at once). It's efficiency (not wasting time waiting).\n\n### Interview Answer\n\n> \"JavaScript is single-threaded - one call stack, one piece of code at a time. Async/await doesn't change that. It lets the thread start an I/O operation, hand it to the OS or browser, and move on to other work. When the result is ready, the callback is queued and the event loop picks it up. It's about efficiency during wait time, not parallel execution. For actual CPU parallelism, you need Web Workers or worker threads.\"",
  "### Theory\n\nA closure is when a function \"remembers\" variables from the scope where it was created, even after that scope has finished executing.\n\n```js\nfunction createCounter() {\n    let count = 0;  // this variable is \"closed over\"\n\n    return function() {\n        count++;\n        return count;\n    };\n}\n\nconst counter = createCounter();\ncounter(); // 1\ncounter(); // 2\ncounter(); // 3\n// count is \"dead\" in normal terms - createCounter finished\n// But the inner function still has access to it\n```\n\n**Practical use cases:**\n```js\n// 1. Data privacy\nfunction createBankAccount(initial) {\n    let balance = initial; // private - can't be accessed directly\n    return {\n        deposit: (amount) => balance += amount,\n        withdraw: (amount) => balance -= amount,\n        getBalance: () => balance\n    };\n}\n\n// 2. Function factories\nfunction multiply(x) {\n    return (y) => x * y; // x is closed over\n}\nconst double = multiply(2);\ndouble(5); // 10\n\n// 3. Event handlers in loops (the fix for the var problem)\n```\n\n### Interview Answer\n\n> \"A closure is a function that retains access to its outer scope's variables even after the outer function has returned. I use closures for data privacy - creating private variables that can only be accessed through returned methods, similar to private fields in OOP. They're also the mechanism behind function factories, currying, and the module pattern. The classic interview example is the var-in-a-loop problem, which closures solve by capturing the value at each iteration.\"",
  "### Theory\n\nJavaScript moves declarations to the top of their scope before executing code. But `var`, `let`, `const`, and functions behave differently.\n\n```js\n// VAR - hoisted and initialized as undefined\nconsole.log(x); // undefined (not an error!)\nvar x = 5;\n// JavaScript sees: var x; console.log(x); x = 5;\n\n// LET/CONST - hoisted but NOT initialized (Temporal Dead Zone)\nconsole.log(y); // ReferenceError: Cannot access 'y' before initialization\nlet y = 5;\n\n// FUNCTION DECLARATION - hoisted entirely (name + body)\nsayHello(); // \"Hello!\" - works before the declaration!\nfunction sayHello() { console.log(\"Hello!\"); }\n\n// FUNCTION EXPRESSION - NOT hoisted\nsayHi(); // TypeError: sayHi is not a function\nvar sayHi = function() { console.log(\"Hi!\"); };\n// var sayHi is hoisted as undefined, but the function assignment isn't\n```\n\n### Interview Answer\n\n> \"Hoisting moves declarations to the top of their scope. var is hoisted and initialized as undefined, so accessing it before declaration gives undefined. let and const are hoisted but NOT initialized - they're in a Temporal Dead Zone until the declaration, causing a ReferenceError. Function declarations are fully hoisted with their body, so you can call them before they appear in code. Function expressions follow the rules of their variable (var/let/const).\"",
  "### Theory\n\n```js\nconst nums = [1, 2, 3];\n\n// MAP - transforms and RETURNS a new array\nconst doubled = nums.map(n => n * 2);  // [2, 4, 6]\n\n// FOREACH - just loops, returns NOTHING (undefined)\nconst result = nums.forEach(n => console.log(n));  // undefined\n```\n\n```\nmap     -> returns new array, doesn't modify original, chainable\nforEach -> returns undefined, just executes, NOT chainable\n```\n\n### Interview Answer\n\n> \"map transforms each element and returns a new array - I use it when I need the results, like rendering a list in React. forEach just iterates with no return value - I use it for side effects like logging. map is chainable: arr.map().filter().reduce(). forEach is not.\"",
  "### Theory\n\nWhen you click a button, the event travels through the DOM in two phases:\n\n```\nCAPTURING (top -> down):  document -> html -> body -> div -> button\nBUBBLING (bottom -> up):  button -> div -> body -> html -> document\n```\n\n```js\n// By default, handlers fire during BUBBLING (bottom up)\nparent.addEventListener(\"click\", () => console.log(\"parent\"));\nchild.addEventListener(\"click\", () => console.log(\"child\"));\n// Click child -> \"child\", \"parent\" (bubbles up)\n\n// Stop bubbling\nchild.addEventListener(\"click\", (e) => {\n    e.stopPropagation(); // parent won't hear about this click\n});\n```\n\n**Event delegation** - instead of attaching listeners to every child, attach one to the parent.\n\n```js\n// Instead of 100 listeners on 100 buttons:\ndocument.getElementById(\"button-container\").addEventListener(\"click\", (e) => {\n    if (e.target.tagName === \"BUTTON\") {\n        console.log(\"Button clicked:\", e.target.textContent);\n    }\n});\n```\n\n### Interview Answer\n\n> \"Events travel down (capturing) then back up (bubbling). By default, handlers fire during the bubbling phase. Event delegation takes advantage of this - attach one listener to a parent instead of many to children. This is more memory efficient and handles dynamically added elements. React uses delegation internally - one listener on the root that routes to the correct component handler.\"",
  "### Theory\n\n```js\n// == (loose equality) - converts types before comparing\n\"5\" == 5      // true - string \"5\" converted to number 5\n0 == false    // true - false converted to 0\nnull == undefined // true - special rule\n\"\" == 0       // true - empty string converted to 0\n\n// === (strict equality) - no conversion, types must match\n\"5\" === 5     // false - string is not number\n0 === false   // false - number is not boolean\nnull === undefined // false - different types\n```\n\n**Always use === unless you have a specific reason for ==.**\n\n### Interview Answer\n\n> \"Double equals does type coercion before comparing - '5' == 5 is true because the string is converted. Triple equals checks type AND value with no conversion - '5' === 5 is false. I always use === to avoid unexpected coercion bugs. The one exception is checking null == undefined, which is true and sometimes useful.\"",
  "### Theory\n\n```js\nconst p1 = fetch(\"/api/users\");     // resolves\nconst p2 = fetch(\"/api/orders\");    // resolves\nconst p3 = fetch(\"/api/broken\");    // rejects\n\n// Promise.all - ALL must succeed, fails fast on first rejection\nawait Promise.all([p1, p2, p3]);    // REJECTS because p3 failed\n\n// Promise.allSettled - waits for ALL, never rejects\nawait Promise.allSettled([p1, p2, p3]);\n// [{status:\"fulfilled\", value:...}, {status:\"fulfilled\", value:...}, {status:\"rejected\", reason:...}]\n\n// Promise.race - first to FINISH (resolve or reject) wins\nawait Promise.race([p1, p2, p3]);   // whichever finishes first\n\n// Promise.any - first to SUCCEED wins, ignores rejections\nawait Promise.any([p1, p2, p3]);    // first resolved value (ignores p3's rejection)\n```\n\n### Interview Answer\n\n> \"Promise.all waits for all and fails fast on any rejection - I use it for parallel independent requests. allSettled waits for everything regardless of success or failure - useful when I need results from all even if some fail. race returns the first to settle - I use it for timeout patterns. any returns the first success, ignoring rejections - useful for trying multiple servers and taking the fastest.\"",
  "```js\nundefined  // variable declared but never assigned\nlet x;\nconsole.log(x); // undefined\n\nnull       // intentionally empty - \"this has no value on purpose\"\nlet user = null; // explicitly set to nothing\n\nNaN        // Not a Number - result of invalid math\n\"hello\" * 5  // NaN\nparseInt(\"abc\") // NaN\n\n// Weirdness\ntypeof undefined  // \"undefined\"\ntypeof null       // \"object\" (famous JS bug, never fixed)\ntypeof NaN        // \"number\" (yes, \"Not a Number\" is a number)\nNaN === NaN       // false! Use Number.isNaN() to check\n```\n\n### Interview Answer\n\n> \"undefined means declared but not assigned - it's JavaScript's default for missing values. null is intentional absence - I set it explicitly. NaN is the result of invalid math operations. The gotcha is typeof null returns 'object' (a long-standing bug) and NaN !== NaN, so you must use Number.isNaN() to check.\"",
  "### Theory\n\nEvery JavaScript object has an internal link to another object called its **prototype**. When you access a property that doesn't exist on the object, JavaScript looks up the prototype chain.\n\n```js\nconst animal = { eats: true, walk() { console.log(\"walking\"); } };\nconst dog = Object.create(animal); // dog's prototype is animal\ndog.barks = true;\n\ndog.barks;  // true - found on dog\ndog.eats;   // true - not on dog, found on prototype (animal)\ndog.walk(); // \"walking\" - found on prototype\n\n// The chain: dog -> animal -> Object.prototype -> null\n```\n\nModern class syntax is syntactic sugar over prototypes:\n```js\nclass Animal { walk() { console.log(\"walking\"); } }\nclass Dog extends Animal { bark() { console.log(\"woof\"); } }\n// Under the hood, Dog.prototype.__proto__ === Animal.prototype\n```\n\n### Interview Answer\n\n> \"JavaScript uses prototypal inheritance - objects have an internal link to a prototype object. When a property isn't found on the object itself, JavaScript walks up the prototype chain. The class syntax is sugar over this mechanism. This is different from classical inheritance in Java or C# where classes are blueprints - in JavaScript, objects inherit directly from other objects.\"",
  "Already covered in the previous artifact. Quick summary:\n\n```\ncall   -> invoke NOW, args one by one:    fn.call(obj, a, b)\napply  -> invoke NOW, args as array:      fn.apply(obj, [a, b])\nbind   -> invoke LATER, returns new fn:   const f = fn.bind(obj)\n```\n\n### Interview Answer\n\n> \"All three set 'this' for a function. call and apply invoke immediately - call takes individual arguments, apply takes an array. bind doesn't invoke - it returns a new function with 'this' permanently set. In modern code, arrow functions and spread syntax have reduced the need, but bind was essential in class component event handlers.\"",
  "### Theory\n\nRegular Map/Set holds strong references - objects inside can never be garbage collected.\n\nWeakMap/WeakSet holds weak references - if nothing else references the key, it can be garbage collected.\n\n```js\n// Regular Map - object stays in memory forever\nconst map = new Map();\nlet user = { name: \"Alice\" };\nmap.set(user, \"data\");\nuser = null; // the object is STILL in the Map, can't be garbage collected\n\n// WeakMap - object can be garbage collected\nconst weakMap = new WeakMap();\nlet user = { name: \"Alice\" };\nweakMap.set(user, \"data\");\nuser = null; // no more references -> garbage collector can free the memory\n```\n\n**Use case:** Caching data about DOM elements or objects without preventing garbage collection.\n\n### Interview Answer\n\n> \"WeakMap and WeakSet hold weak references to keys - if the key object has no other references, it can be garbage collected. I use WeakMap for metadata caching - like storing computed data about DOM elements. When the element is removed from the DOM, the cache entry is automatically cleaned up. Regular Maps would cause memory leaks in this scenario.\"",
  "### Theory\n\nThe time between entering a scope and the let/const declaration. Variables exist but can't be accessed.\n\n```js\n{\n    // TDZ for x starts here\n    console.log(x); // ReferenceError!\n    // x exists but isn't initialized - Temporal Dead Zone\n    let x = 5;      // TDZ ends here\n    console.log(x); // 5 - now it works\n}\n```\n\nvar doesn't have TDZ - it's initialized as undefined immediately.\n\n### Interview Answer\n\n> \"The TDZ is the period between entering a scope and the let/const declaration where the variable exists but can't be accessed. Accessing it throws a ReferenceError. This prevents the confusing behavior of var where you could use a variable before declaring it and get undefined. TDZ makes code behavior more predictable.\"",
  "### Theory\n\nA function that can **pause and resume**. Uses `function*` and `yield`.\n\n```js\nfunction* countUp() {\n    yield 1;    // pause, return 1\n    yield 2;    // pause, return 2\n    yield 3;    // pause, return 3\n}\n\nconst gen = countUp();\ngen.next(); // { value: 1, done: false }\ngen.next(); // { value: 2, done: false }\ngen.next(); // { value: 3, done: false }\ngen.next(); // { value: undefined, done: true }\n\n// Practical: infinite sequence\nfunction* fibonacci() {\n    let a = 0, b = 1;\n    while (true) {\n        yield a;\n        [a, b] = [b, a + b];\n    }\n}\nconst fib = fibonacci();\nfib.next().value; // 0\nfib.next().value; // 1\nfib.next().value; // 1\nfib.next().value; // 2\n```\n\n### Interview Answer\n\n> \"Generators are functions that can pause with yield and resume with next(). They're lazy - they compute values on demand. I use them for infinite sequences, paginated data iteration, and managing async flows in Redux Saga. Under the hood, async/await was inspired by generators.\"",
  "### Theory\n\nCache function results so repeated calls with the same arguments don't recalculate.\n\n```js\nfunction memoize(fn) {\n    const cache = new Map();\n\n    return function(...args) {\n        const key = JSON.stringify(args);\n        if (cache.has(key)) return cache.get(key);\n\n        const result = fn.apply(this, args);\n        cache.set(key, result);\n        return result;\n    };\n}\n\nconst expensiveCalc = memoize((n) => {\n    console.log(\"Computing...\");\n    return n * n;\n});\n\nexpensiveCalc(5); // \"Computing...\" -> 25\nexpensiveCalc(5); // 25 (no \"Computing...\" - cached!)\nexpensiveCalc(3); // \"Computing...\" -> 9\n```\n\n### Interview Answer\n\n> \"Memoization caches function results by arguments so repeated calls skip the computation. I implement it with a closure over a Map, using serialized arguments as keys. React's useMemo is essentially memoization for computed values within a component. It's great for expensive calculations but adds memory overhead, so I use it selectively.\"",
  "### Theory\n\n```js\nconst original = { name: \"Alice\", address: { city: \"NYC\" } };\n\n// SHALLOW - copies top level, nested objects are still SHARED\nconst shallow = { ...original };\nshallow.name = \"Bob\";          // doesn't affect original [ok]\nshallow.address.city = \"LA\";   // CHANGES original! X - shared reference\n\n// DEEP - everything is independent\nconst deep = JSON.parse(JSON.stringify(original)); // simple but loses functions, dates\nconst deep2 = structuredClone(original);            // modern, handles more types\n```\n\n### Interview Answer\n\n> \"Shallow copy duplicates the top level - nested objects are still shared references. Deep copy creates independent copies at every level. For shallow, I use spread or Object.assign. For deep, structuredClone is the modern approach. JSON parse/stringify works but loses functions, undefined, dates, and circular references.\"",
  "### Theory\n\nTransform a function with multiple arguments into a chain of single-argument functions.\n\n```js\n// Normal\nconst add = (a, b, c) => a + b + c;\nadd(1, 2, 3); // 6\n\n// Curried\nconst add = a => b => c => a + b + c;\nadd(1)(2)(3); // 6\n\n// Practical: create specialized functions\nconst log = level => message => `[${level}] ${message}`;\nconst error = log(\"ERROR\");\nerror(\"DB down\"); // \"[ERROR] DB down\"\n```\n\n### Interview Answer\n\n> \"Currying transforms a multi-argument function into single-argument functions. The practical benefit is creating reusable, partially applied functions - like a generic logger curried into specific error or info loggers. It's common in functional programming and libraries like Lodash.\"",
  "### Theory\n\nA Proxy wraps an object and lets you intercept/customize operations on it.\n\n```js\nconst user = { name: \"Alice\", age: 25 };\n\nconst proxy = new Proxy(user, {\n    get(target, prop) {\n        console.log(`Reading ${prop}`);\n        return target[prop];\n    },\n    set(target, prop, value) {\n        if (prop === \"age\" && value < 0) throw new Error(\"Age can't be negative\");\n        target[prop] = value;\n        return true;\n    }\n});\n\nproxy.name;      // logs \"Reading name\", returns \"Alice\"\nproxy.age = -5;  // throws Error!\n```\n\n**Use cases:** Validation, logging, Vue.js reactivity system, API mocking.\n\n### Interview Answer\n\n> \"Proxy intercepts operations on objects - reads, writes, function calls, even property deletion. I've seen it used for input validation, change tracking, and it's the foundation of Vue 3's reactivity system. It's powerful but has performance overhead, so I use it for cross-cutting concerns, not hot paths.\"",
  "```js\n// COMMONJS (Node.js traditional)\nconst express = require(\"express\");       // sync, dynamic\nmodule.exports = { myFunction };\n\n// ES MODULES (modern standard)\nimport express from \"express\";            // static, analyzed at build time\nexport const myFunction = () => {};\n```\n\n```\nCommonJS -> synchronous, runs at runtime, Node.js default\nES Modules -> static, analyzed at build, tree-shakeable, browser native\n```\n\n### Interview Answer\n\n> \"CommonJS uses require/module.exports and loads synchronously at runtime - traditional in Node.js. ES Modules use import/export, are statically analyzed at build time, and enable tree-shaking to remove unused code. Modern projects use ES Modules for both browser and server code. Node.js supports both.\"",
  "### Theory\n\nSymbols are unique, immutable identifiers - guaranteed to never collide with anything.\n\n```js\nconst id1 = Symbol(\"id\");\nconst id2 = Symbol(\"id\");\nid1 === id2; // false! - every Symbol is unique\n\n// Use case: hidden/private-ish object properties\nconst SECRET = Symbol(\"secret\");\nconst user = { name: \"Alice\", [SECRET]: \"password123\" };\nObject.keys(user);        // [\"name\"] - Symbol is hidden\nJSON.stringify(user);      // '{\"name\":\"Alice\"}' - Symbol excluded\nuser[SECRET];              // \"password123\" - accessible if you have the Symbol\n```\n\n### Interview Answer\n\n> \"Symbols are unique primitive values, mainly used as property keys that won't collide with other keys. They don't appear in Object.keys or JSON.stringify, making them useful for metadata or framework-internal properties. Well-known Symbols like Symbol.iterator let you customize object behavior like making something iterable with for...of.\""
];

export const nodeAnswers: string[] = [
  "### Theory\n\nNode.js runs on a single thread. On an 8-core machine, 7 cores sit idle. Clusters fork the process so each core runs a copy of your server.\n\n```js\nconst cluster = require(\"cluster\");\nconst os = require(\"os\");\n\nif (cluster.isPrimary) {\n    const cpuCount = os.cpus().length;\n    for (let i = 0; i < cpuCount; i++) {\n        cluster.fork(); // create a worker per core\n    }\n    cluster.on(\"exit\", (worker) => {\n        cluster.fork(); // restart crashed workers\n    });\n} else {\n    // Each worker runs the server\n    const app = require(\"./app\");\n    app.listen(3000);\n}\n```\n\n### Interview Answer\n\n> \"Node clusters fork the process across CPU cores. The primary process manages workers; each worker runs the server independently. The OS load-balances requests across workers. I also restart crashed workers automatically. In production, I'd use PM2 which handles clustering, monitoring, and restarts out of the box.\"",
  "### Theory\n\n**Vertical:** Bigger machine (more RAM, CPU). Limited.\n**Horizontal:** Multiple instances behind a load balancer. Scalable.\n\n```\nStrategies:\n1. Clustering - use all CPU cores\n2. Load balancer (Nginx, AWS ALB) - distribute across multiple servers\n3. Stateless design - no server-side sessions (use JWT, Redis)\n4. Caching - Redis for frequent reads\n5. Queues - offload heavy work to background workers\n6. Database optimization - indexes, connection pooling, read replicas\n7. CDN - serve static files from edge servers\n```\n\n### Interview Answer\n\n> \"I scale Node horizontally: clustering for multi-core utilization, load balancing across multiple instances, stateless design with JWT so any instance can handle any request, Redis for caching and session storage, message queues for offloading heavy processing, and database read replicas for read-heavy workloads.\"",
  "### Theory\n\nPrevents abuse by limiting how many requests a client can make in a time window.\n\n```js\nconst rateLimit = require(\"express-rate-limit\");\n\nconst limiter = rateLimit({\n    windowMs: 15 * 60 * 1000,  // 15 minutes\n    max: 100,                    // 100 requests per window per IP\n    message: { error: \"Too many requests, try again later\" }\n});\n\napp.use(\"/api/\", limiter);\n```\n\nFor distributed systems (multiple servers), use Redis-backed rate limiting so limits are shared.\n\n### Interview Answer\n\n> \"Rate limiting restricts request count per client within a time window. I use express-rate-limit for single instances and Redis-backed solutions for distributed setups so limits are shared across servers. Different endpoints get different limits - login gets stricter limits to prevent brute force, public APIs get standard limits.\"",
  "### Theory\n\nHelmet sets security-related HTTP headers to protect against common attacks.\n\n```js\nconst helmet = require(\"helmet\");\napp.use(helmet());\n\n// Sets headers like:\n// X-Content-Type-Options: nosniff  -> prevents MIME sniffing\n// X-Frame-Options: DENY            -> prevents clickjacking\n// Strict-Transport-Security        -> forces HTTPS\n// X-XSS-Protection                 -> prevents XSS in older browsers\n// Content-Security-Policy          -> controls what resources can load\n```\n\n### Interview Answer\n\n> \"Helmet sets security headers automatically - preventing clickjacking with X-Frame-Options, MIME sniffing with nosniff, forcing HTTPS with HSTS, and controlling resource loading with CSP. It's a single middleware call that addresses multiple OWASP top-10 vulnerabilities.\"",
  "### Theory\n\n**CORS (Cross-Origin Resource Sharing)** - browser blocks requests from one origin to another by default. Your React app on localhost:3000 can't call your API on localhost:5000 unless the API explicitly allows it.\n\n```js\nconst cors = require(\"cors\");\n\n// Allow specific origin\napp.use(cors({\n    origin: \"https://myapp.com\",\n    methods: [\"GET\", \"POST\", \"PUT\", \"DELETE\"],\n    credentials: true  // allow cookies\n}));\n```\n\n### Interview Answer\n\n> \"CORS is a browser security mechanism that blocks cross-origin requests. The server must explicitly allow origins through the Access-Control-Allow-Origin header. I configure it with specific allowed origins rather than wildcard '*', especially when credentials are involved. The browser sends a preflight OPTIONS request for non-simple methods.\"",
  "### Theory\n\n**Command Query Responsibility Segregation** - separate the read model from the write model.\n\n```\nTRADITIONAL:  One model for both reads and writes\nCQRS:         Separate models optimized for their purpose\n\nWRITE side (Commands): normalized, validates, enforces rules\nREAD side (Queries):   denormalized, fast, pre-joined, possibly cached\n```\n\n**Use when:** Read and write patterns are very different - heavy reads need denormalized data, writes need strict validation. Not for simple CRUD.\n\n### Interview Answer\n\n> \"CQRS separates read and write models. The write side enforces business rules on a normalized schema. The read side uses denormalized, pre-computed views optimized for queries. I'd use it when read and write patterns diverge significantly - like a dashboard reading aggregated data while transactions write to normalized tables. For simple CRUD, it's unnecessary complexity.\"",
  "```\nPUT   -> replace the ENTIRE resource\nPATCH -> update ONLY specific fields\n```\n\n```js\n// PUT - send the complete object\nPUT /api/users/1\n{ \"name\": \"Alice\", \"email\": \"alice@new.com\", \"age\": 26 }\n// Missing fields are set to null/default\n\n// PATCH - send only what changed\nPATCH /api/users/1\n{ \"email\": \"alice@new.com\" }\n// Only email changes, name and age stay the same\n```\n\n### Interview Answer\n\n> \"PUT replaces the entire resource - you must send all fields. PATCH updates only the specified fields. I use PATCH for most updates since clients usually change one or two fields. PUT is for when the client has the complete updated resource.\"",
  "### Theory\n\nUsed for file uploads. Regular JSON can't handle binary files.\n\n```js\nconst multer = require(\"multer\");\nconst upload = multer({ dest: \"uploads/\" });\n\napp.post(\"/upload\", upload.single(\"avatar\"), (req, res) => {\n    console.log(req.file);    // uploaded file info\n    console.log(req.body);    // other form fields\n    res.json({ filename: req.file.filename });\n});\n```\n\n### Interview Answer\n\n> \"Multipart/form-data is the encoding type for file uploads - it splits the request into parts for binary files and text fields. I use Multer middleware in Express to parse uploads, with options for file size limits, allowed types, and storage destination.\"",
  "### Theory\n\nThe HTTP spec says GET CAN have a body, but it SHOULD NOT. Most servers, proxies, and caches ignore or strip it. Don't do it.\n\n### Interview Answer\n\n> \"Technically the HTTP spec doesn't prohibit it, but practically it's a bad idea - many proxies, caches, and frameworks ignore or strip GET bodies. For complex query parameters, I use POST with a body or encode parameters in the query string.\"",
  "```\nGET     -> read data, no body, cacheable, idempotent\nPOST    -> create new resource, has body, NOT idempotent\nPUT     -> replace entire resource, idempotent\nPATCH   -> partial update, idempotent\nDELETE  -> remove resource, idempotent\nHEAD    -> like GET but returns only headers (check if resource exists)\nOPTIONS -> returns allowed methods (used in CORS preflight)\n```\n\n### Interview Answer\n\n> \"GET retrieves data and is cacheable. POST creates resources. PUT replaces entirely, PATCH updates partially - both are idempotent. DELETE removes. HEAD is GET without a body - useful for checking if a file exists. OPTIONS returns allowed methods and is used in CORS preflight requests.\"",
  "```\nHASHING    -> one-way, can't reverse. Same input always gives same output.\n              Use for: passwords, integrity checks\n              Example: bcrypt(\"password123\") -> \"$2b$10$xyz...\"\n\nENCRYPTION -> two-way, can decrypt with a key.\n              Use for: sensitive data you need back (credit cards, messages)\n              Example: encrypt(\"secret\", key) -> \"abc123\" -> decrypt(\"abc123\", key) -> \"secret\"\n```\n\n### Interview Answer\n\n> \"Hashing is one-way - you can't get the original back. I use bcrypt for passwords because even I shouldn't be able to read them. Encryption is two-way with a key - I use it for data I need to retrieve, like credit card numbers. Never encrypt passwords - if the key leaks, all passwords are exposed. Hash them.\"",
  "### Theory\n\nBoth have microtasks and macrotasks, but Node has extra phases:\n\n```\nNode Event Loop Phases:\n1. timers          - setTimeout, setInterval callbacks\n2. pending I/O     - system operations\n3. idle/prepare    - internal\n4. poll            - incoming connections, data, etc.\n5. check           - setImmediate callbacks\n6. close           - socket.on(\"close\") callbacks\n\nBetween each phase: ALL microtasks (Promises, process.nextTick)\n```\n\nBrowser is simpler: macrotask -> all microtasks -> render -> repeat.\n\n### Interview Answer\n\n> \"Both use microtasks and macrotasks, but Node's loop has six distinct phases - timers, I/O, poll, check, close. The browser has a simpler model with a rendering step. Node also has process.nextTick which fires before any other microtask, and setImmediate which fires in the check phase after I/O.\"",
  "### Theory\n\nMiddleware functions sit between the request and response. They can modify req/res, end the response, or call next() to pass to the next middleware.\n\n```js\n// Middleware chain: logger -> auth -> route handler\n\nfunction logger(req, res, next) {\n    console.log(`${req.method} ${req.path}`);\n    next(); // pass to next middleware\n}\n\nfunction auth(req, res, next) {\n    if (!req.headers.authorization) {\n        return res.status(401).json({ error: \"Not authorized\" });\n        // NO next() - stops the chain\n    }\n    next(); // pass to next\n}\n\napp.use(logger);     // runs on every request\napp.use(\"/api\", auth); // runs on /api routes only\napp.get(\"/api/users\", (req, res) => {\n    res.json(users); // final handler\n});\n```\n\n### Interview Answer\n\n> \"Middleware functions receive req, res, and next. They can modify the request, send a response, or call next() to continue the chain. I use them for logging, authentication, validation, error handling, and rate limiting. The order matters - they execute in the order they're registered.\"",
  "```js\nsetTimeout(() => console.log(\"timeout\"), 0);       // timers phase\nsetImmediate(() => console.log(\"immediate\"));       // check phase\nprocess.nextTick(() => console.log(\"nextTick\"));    // before anything else\n\n// Output: nextTick, timeout/immediate (order between these two varies)\n```\n\n```\nprocess.nextTick -> fires BEFORE any I/O or timer, highest priority microtask\nsetImmediate     -> fires in the \"check\" phase, AFTER I/O\nsetTimeout(0)    -> fires in the \"timers\" phase\n```\n\n### Interview Answer\n\n> \"process.nextTick fires before any other async callback - even before Promises. It's useful for deferring work but can starve the event loop if overused. setImmediate fires in the check phase after I/O events. setTimeout with 0 fires in the timers phase. In I/O callbacks, setImmediate always fires before setTimeout(0).\"",
  "```js\n// Catch uncaught exceptions\nprocess.on(\"uncaughtException\", (err) => {\n    console.error(\"Uncaught:\", err);\n    process.exit(1); // app is in unknown state - must exit\n});\n\n// Catch unhandled promise rejections\nprocess.on(\"unhandledRejection\", (reason) => {\n    console.error(\"Unhandled rejection:\", reason);\n    process.exit(1);\n});\n```\n\n### Interview Answer\n\n> \"I set up global handlers for both, but they're last-resort safety nets. uncaughtException means the app is in an unknown state - I log the error, notify monitoring, and exit. A process manager like PM2 restarts the process. The real solution is proper try-catch and .catch() so these handlers rarely fire.\"",
  "### Theory\n\nStreams process data in chunks instead of loading everything into memory.\n\n```js\n// WITHOUT streams - 2GB file loads entirely into memory\nconst data = fs.readFileSync(\"huge-file.csv\"); // 2GB in RAM!\n\n// WITH streams - processes chunk by chunk\nconst readable = fs.createReadStream(\"huge-file.csv\");\nconst writable = fs.createWriteStream(\"output.csv\");\n\nreadable.pipe(writable); // chunks flow through without loading entire file\n\n// Transform stream - modify data as it flows\nconst { Transform } = require(\"stream\");\nconst uppercase = new Transform({\n    transform(chunk, encoding, callback) {\n        callback(null, chunk.toString().toUpperCase());\n    }\n});\n\nreadable.pipe(uppercase).pipe(writable);\n```\n\n```\nReadable  -> source of data (file read, HTTP request body)\nWritable  -> destination (file write, HTTP response)\nTransform -> modify data flowing through (compression, encryption)\nDuplex    -> both readable and writable (TCP socket)\n```\n\n### Interview Answer\n\n> \"Streams process data in chunks instead of buffering everything in memory. A 2GB file doesn't need 2GB of RAM - it's processed piece by piece. I use readable streams for file/HTTP input, writable for output, and transform for processing in between - like compressing a file while reading and writing simultaneously. Pipe connects them cleanly.\"",
  "### Theory\n\n**JWT (JSON Web Token)** - a self-contained token that carries user info, signed by the server.\n\n```\nStructure: header.payload.signature\n\nheader:    {\"alg\": \"HS256\", \"typ\": \"JWT\"}\npayload:   {\"userId\": 42, \"role\": \"admin\", \"exp\": 1234567890}\nsignature: HMAC(header + payload, SECRET_KEY)\n```\n\n```js\nconst jwt = require(\"jsonwebtoken\");\n\n// LOGIN - create token\napp.post(\"/login\", async (req, res) => {\n    const user = await verifyCredentials(req.body);\n    const token = jwt.sign(\n        { userId: user.id, role: user.role },\n        process.env.JWT_SECRET,\n        { expiresIn: \"1h\" }\n    );\n    res.json({ token });\n});\n\n// MIDDLEWARE - verify token on protected routes\nfunction authMiddleware(req, res, next) {\n    const token = req.headers.authorization?.split(\" \")[1]; // \"Bearer xxx\"\n    if (!token) return res.status(401).json({ error: \"No token\" });\n\n    try {\n        const decoded = jwt.verify(token, process.env.JWT_SECRET);\n        req.user = decoded; // { userId: 42, role: \"admin\" }\n        next();\n    } catch {\n        res.status(401).json({ error: \"Invalid token\" });\n    }\n}\n\napp.get(\"/api/profile\", authMiddleware, (req, res) => {\n    res.json({ userId: req.user.userId });\n});\n```\n\n### Interview Answer\n\n> \"JWT is a self-contained token carrying user claims, signed by the server. On login, I create a token with user ID and role, sign it with a secret, and set an expiration. On protected routes, middleware extracts the token from the Authorization header, verifies the signature, and attaches the decoded user to the request. The server never stores sessions - any instance can verify the token independently, making it great for stateless horizontal scaling.\"",
  "### Theory\n\nOpening a database connection for every request is slow. A connection pool maintains a set of reusable connections.\n\n```js\nconst { Pool } = require(\"pg\");\n\nconst pool = new Pool({\n    host: \"localhost\",\n    database: \"mydb\",\n    max: 20,        // max 20 connections\n    idleTimeoutMillis: 30000\n});\n\n// Request comes in -> borrows connection from pool -> uses it -> returns it\napp.get(\"/users\", async (req, res) => {\n    const client = await pool.query(\"SELECT * FROM users\");\n    // Connection returned to pool automatically\n    res.json(client.rows);\n});\n```\n\n### Interview Answer\n\n> \"Connection pooling maintains reusable database connections instead of creating and destroying one per request. Opening a connection involves TCP handshake, authentication, and SSL - expensive per request. A pool of 20 connections can serve thousands of requests per second by reusing them. I configure pool size based on database limits and expected concurrency.\"",
  "### Theory\n\nHeavy work like report generation, email sending, or image processing shouldn't block the request.\n\n```js\nconst { Queue, Worker } = require(\"bullmq\");\nconst Redis = require(\"ioredis\");\n\nconst connection = new Redis();\n\n// PRODUCER - add jobs from your API\nconst emailQueue = new Queue(\"email\", { connection });\n\napp.post(\"/api/orders\", async (req, res) => {\n    const order = await createOrder(req.body);\n    await emailQueue.add(\"confirmation\", { orderId: order.id, email: req.body.email });\n    res.json(order); // respond immediately, email sends in background\n});\n\n// WORKER - processes jobs separately\nconst worker = new Worker(\"email\", async (job) => {\n    await sendEmail(job.data.email, `Order ${job.data.orderId} confirmed!`);\n}, { connection });\n```\n\n### Interview Answer\n\n> \"I use BullMQ with Redis for background jobs. The API enqueues a job and responds immediately - the worker processes it asynchronously. This handles retries, delays, rate limiting, and dead letter queues. Use cases: email sending, report generation, image processing, data imports - anything that takes more than a second.\"",
  "### Theory\n\nWhen you deploy new code, you can't just kill the process - in-flight requests would fail. Graceful shutdown stops accepting new requests, finishes existing ones, closes connections, then exits.\n\n```js\nconst server = app.listen(3000);\n\nfunction gracefulShutdown(signal) {\n    console.log(`${signal} received. Shutting down gracefully...`);\n\n    server.close(() => {\n        console.log(\"HTTP server closed - no new connections\");\n\n        // Close database connections\n        pool.end(() => {\n            console.log(\"Database pool closed\");\n\n            // Close Redis, queues, etc.\n            redis.quit(() => {\n                console.log(\"Redis closed\");\n                process.exit(0);\n            });\n        });\n    });\n\n    // Force kill after 30 seconds if graceful shutdown hangs\n    setTimeout(() => {\n        console.error(\"Forced shutdown after timeout\");\n        process.exit(1);\n    }, 30000);\n}\n\nprocess.on(\"SIGTERM\", gracefulShutdown); // Docker/Kubernetes sends this\nprocess.on(\"SIGINT\", gracefulShutdown);  // Ctrl+C sends this\n```\n\n### Interview Answer\n\n> \"Graceful shutdown listens for SIGTERM/SIGINT, stops accepting new connections, waits for in-flight requests to complete, closes database pools and Redis connections, then exits. I add a timeout as a safety net - if cleanup takes too long, force-kill. This prevents dropped requests during deployments and ensures data integrity for transactions in progress.\""
];
